ariants":[{"name":"Cogen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Dorith.  German Erwin.","Variant of   Cogan  ."]},{"name":"Coggin","meanings":["English: variant of   Cogan  ."]},{"name":"Cohen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Isadore, Emanuel, Moshe, Shlomo, Myer, Avi, Yehuda, Chaim.","Jewish: from Hebrew <i>kohen</i> ‘priest’. Priests are traditionally regarded as members of a hereditary caste descended from Aaron, brother of Moses. See also   Kaplan  .","Irish (Galway and Sligo): variant of   Coyne  ."]},{"name":"Coggins","meanings":["English: variant of   Cogan  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Coggan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Conal, Seamus.  Jewish Hyman.","English: variant of   Cogan  .","Americanized form of Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic) <b>Kogan</b>, from the Russian pronunciation of   Cohen  ."]}]},{"name":"Juliana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Julianus</i> (  see  Julian  ), which was revived in England in the 18th century and has been used occasionally ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Juliana Cogan was born about 1200, in County Offaly, Ireland as the daughter of Sir John de Cogan and Marie de Prendergast. She married Maurice FitzGerald de Berminham 2nd Lord of Offaly in 1214, in Aberdare, Mid Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died in 1257, in her hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"Abt 1200–1257":"umbes 1200–1257","1200–1257":"1200–1257","1194–1257":"1194–1257","1215–1243":"1215–1243","1216–1271":"1216–1271","1218–1277":"1218–1277","1221–Male":"1221–Surnud","1229–1271":"1229–1271","–1271":"–1271","–1278":"–1278","1176–Female":"1176–Surnud","1176":"1176","1271":"1271","1194":"1194","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1257":"1257","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1278":"1278","abo